At the recent conference “Unmanned Aviation in Logistics - Moving Up,” CEO of BAS LLC Alexey Varyatchenko made a report, talking about the Russian market and his company’s capabilities in unmanned logistics.

Operator "BAS", if anyone doesn't remember, was created by State Transport Leasing Company and NTI to provide services for the transportation of goods by unmanned aircraft.

The logistics and last mile delivery market in 2025-2030 is estimated by BAS at 25 billion rubles. We are talking here about delivery to distribution hubs in remote regions of the country, and about delivery to hard-to-reach regions outside cities, and about delivery within cities. Although at the same conference we already heard that we are unlikely to see urban delivery in the near future. But let's get back to the numbers:

● the market capacity for the use of UAS in 2025-2030 in agriculture is estimated at 21.1 billion rubles;

● in construction - 18.1 billion rubles;

● the market for monitoring infrastructure facilities using UAVs is estimated at 14 billion rubles;

● monitoring of pollution and ecology, detection and prevention of fires - 12.8 billion rubles;

● public safety, search for missing people and other purposes - 9.2 billion rubles.

Very small market volumes in the fuel and energy complex, mining and processing - 4.3 billion rubles, and in inventory and warehouse logistics they still prefer robots rather than UAS. There the market volume is only 2.2 billion rubles.

But perhaps the most interesting figures concern personnel. Thanks to the UAS report, we finally know how many people it takes to screw in a light bulb to maintain heavy logistics UAS.

Judging by the company’s calculations, for one unmanned aircraft system weighing more than 30 kg there are 44 employees with confirmed professional education. Here you have seven external pilots, five technical instructors, two programmers, and eleven managers of different levels and stripes. Did anyone think that the drone actually flies on its own?

